Title: Will be included in every table
One row per subject per study

column10: An identifier assigned to a data contributor.
A sequence of characters used to identify, name, or characterize the study.
The current status of the subject's enrollment.
column12: Note: refers to if subject was enrolled in the study, or subject was not enrolled in the study but received treatment per the study's protocol.

Title: One row per subject per disease phase(s)

column10: The stage or period of an individual's disease.
column12: Note: Disease phase could be "Initial Diagnosis" phase, a "Relapse" phase, or a "Progression" phase.

Title: AGE_AT_DISEASE_PHASE
column6: Age in Days at Disease Phase

Title: One row per subject per course(s)

column10: The type of protocol treatment course administered.

Title: AGE_AT_COURSE_START
column6: Age in Days at Course Start

Title: AGE_AT_COURSE_END
column6: Age in Days at Course End

Title: One row per subject per off protocol therapy or off study per reason off
AGE_OFF
column6: Age in Days When Off Protocol Therapy or Study

column10: The stage or period of an individual's disease.
column12: Note: Disease phase could be "Initial Diagnosis" phase, a "Relapse" phase, or a "Progression" phase.

column10: The type of protocol treatment course administered.
The code used to designate that the subject went off therapy or off the study.

Title: REASON_OFF
column6: Off Protocol Therapy or Study Reason

column10: A coded value specifying why the subject is removed from a study.
column12: Note: If multiple reasons off, include one observation per reason off.

Title: ANOTHER_STUDY
column6: Enrolled in Another Therapeutic Study After Off Study

column10: The subject was enrolled in another therapeutic study after the off protocol study.
The assemblage of physical properties or qualities by which male is distinguished from female; the physical difference between male and female; the distinguishing peculiarity of male or female.

An arbitrary classification of a taxonomic group that is a division of a species. It usually arises as a consequence of geographical isolation within a species and is characterized by shared heredity, physical attributes and behavior, and in the case of humans, by common history, nationality, or geographic distribution.

column8: Native Hawaiian or Other Pacific Islander

column10: A social group characterized by a distinctive social and cultural tradition that is maintained from generation to generation. Members share a common history and origin and a sense of identification with the group. They have similar and distinctive features in their lifestyle habits and shared experiences. They often have a common genetic heritage which may be reflected in their experience of health and disease.

column10: The individual's last known survival status.

column6: Last Known Survival Status with Disease

column10: The last know survival status of the individual with the disease.

column6: Age in Days When Lost to Follow-up

column10: The circumstance or condition that results in the death of a living being.
column12: Note: If multiple causes of death, include one observation per cause of death.

column10: The type of treatment related to the mortality of the subject.
column12: Note: If multiple treatment types, include one observation per treatment type.

column10: Specific details of the cause of death.
column12: Note: If multiple cause of death details, include one observation per cause of death detail.

column10: Assigning a weighted relevance to the cause of death.
column12: Note: Contributory refers to additional cause of death, not necessarily the ordinal ranking of causes of death. There may be multiple secondary causes of death.

Title: One row per subject per disease phase per disease site

column10: The stage or period of an individual's disease.

Leukemia with an acute onset, characterized by the presence of lymphoblasts in the bone marrow and the peripheral blood. It includes the acute B lymphoblastic leukemia and acute T lymphoblastic leukemia.

column8: Acute Leukemia, ambiguous lineage (mixed or biphenotypic)

column10: The anatomic site of the disease.
column12: Note: If multiple sites of disease involvement, include one observation per site.

column10: The status of central nervous system leukemia at the time of diagnosis.

When the maximum width of a mass is equal or greater than one-third of the internal transverse diameter of the thorax at the level of T5/6 on a PA CXR. Bulk at an alternate site is defined as any mass measuring 10 cm or more by any imaging study.

Title: PRIOR_STEROIDS_WEEK

Title: PRIOR_STEROIDS_MONTH
column6: Subject Received Steroids Within One Month Prior to Diagnosis of Disease Phase

column10: The subject received steroids within one month prior to diagnosis of the disease phase.

Title: One row per subject per vitals sign record

column10: The stage or period of an individual's disease.
column12: Note: Disease phase could be "Initial Diagnosis" phase, a "Relapse" phase, or a "Progression" phase.

column10: The type of protocol treatment course administered.
The act of assessing an individual's current temperature, heart rate, respiratory rate, pulse oxygenation, and blood pressure.
The unit used to record and describe the result of a test investigating a vital sign.

Title: One row per subject per lab value
AGE_AT_LAB
column6: Age in Days of Lab Test

column10: A classification of the laboratory test.
A character or string that represents the full name of the laboratory assessment.
The type of a material sample taken from a biological entity for laboratory testing.
The numeric unit that expresses the lab result.
A systematic course of action that is performed in order to complete a laboratory test.
The morphology characteristics of the bone marrow blasts.

Title: TRAUMATIC_TAP
column6: Lumbar Puncture Artifically Contaminated by Peripheral Blood

column10: Contamination of a cerebrospinal fluid sample by red blood cells greater than 10/mm3.
column12: Notes: Traumatic tap is defined as cerebrospinal fluid with greater than 10 RBC/mm3.

The anatomic source of the molecular analysis sample.
The status of the subject's karyotype.
A molecular or cytogenic abnormality which occurs in either human disease states or disease models.
column12: Note: If multiple molecular abnormalities, include one observation per molecular abnormality.

column10: A variation in or modification of the molecular sequence of a gene or gene product.
An indicator for whether a molecular analysis procedure was performed and whether the assay detected a molecular abnormality.
column12: Note: This variable indicates the result of testing for the molecular abnormality listed in MOLECULAR_ABNORMALITY

column10: The finding of the chromosomal translocation analysis.

A process in which blood or tissue samples are analyzed to determine their human leukocyte antigen (HLA) profiles so that transplant materials can be transferred into a patient with the same or similar profile.
